 265:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c **** /*
 266:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   Blocks the thread while waiting for the semaphore to be
 267:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   signaled. If the "timeout" argument is non-zero, the thread should
 268:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   only be blocked for the specified time (measured in
 269:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   milliseconds).
 270:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c **** 
 271:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   If the timeout argument is non-zero, the return value is the number of
 272:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   milliseconds spent waiting for the semaphore to be signaled. If the
 273:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   semaphore wasn't signaled within the specified time, the return value is
 274:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   SYS_ARCH_TIMEOUT. If the thread didn't have to wait for the semaphore
 275:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   (i.e., it was already signaled), the function may return zero.
 276:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c **** 
 277:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   Notice that lwIP implements a function with a similar name,
 278:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c ****   sys_sem_wait(), that uses the sys_arch_sem_wait() function.
 279:Middlewares/Third_Party/LwIP/system/OS/sys_arch.c **** */
